
TY  - JOUR
T1  - It Takes a Village: The Economics of Parenting with Neighborhood                         and Peer Effects
AU  - Agostinelli, Francesco
AU  - Doepke, Matthias
AU  - Sorrenti, Giuseppe
AU  - Zilibotti, Fabrizio
Y1  - 2025/10/28
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2026/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/739334
DO  - 10.1086/739334
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 313
EP  - 365
VL  - 134
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - During adolescence, peer interactions become increasingly central to children?s development, whereas the direct influence of parents wanes. Nevertheless, parents can continue to exert leverage by shaping their children?s peer groups. We construct and estimate a model of parenting with peer and neighborhood effects where parents intervene in peer formation and show that the model captures empirical patterns of skill accumulation, parenting style, and peer characteristics among US high school students. We find that interventions that move children to better neighborhoods lose impact when they are scaled up, because parents? equilibrium responses push against successful integration with the new peer group.
AB  - During adolescence, peer interactions become increasingly central to children?s development, whereas the direct influence of parents wanes. Nevertheless, parents can continue to exert leverage by shaping their children?s peer groups. We construct and estimate a model of parenting with peer and neighborhood effects where parents intervene in peer formation and show that the model captures empirical patterns of skill accumulation, parenting style, and peer characteristics among US high school students. We find that interventions that move children to better neighborhoods lose impact when they are scaled up, because parents? equilibrium responses push against successful integration with the new peer group.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/739334
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/739334
Y2  - 2026/04/24
