TY  - JOUR
T1  - Why Don’t Struggling Students Do Their Homework? Disentangling                         Motivation and Study Productivity as Drivers of Human Capital                         Formation
AU  - Cotton, Christopher S.
AU  - Hickman, Brent R.
AU  - List, John A.
AU  - Price, Joseph
AU  - Roy, Sutanuka
Y1  - 2025/09/04
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2026/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738479
DO  - 10.1086/738479
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 86
EP  - 149
VL  - 134
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Using field experimental data (study time tracking and randomized incentives), we identify a structural model of learning. Student effort is influenced by external costs/benefits and unobserved heterogeneity: motivation (willingness to study) and productivity (conversion rate of time into skill). We estimate academic labor supply elasticities and skill technology. Productivity and motivation are uncorrelated. Low productivity, not low motivation, is the stronger predictor of academic struggles. School quality augments productivity and accelerates skill production. We find that dynamic skill complementarities arise mainly from children?s aging and from a feedback loop between investment activity and productivity rather than from carrying forward past skill stocks.
AB  - Using field experimental data (study time tracking and randomized incentives), we identify a structural model of learning. Student effort is influenced by external costs/benefits and unobserved heterogeneity: motivation (willingness to study) and productivity (conversion rate of time into skill). We estimate academic labor supply elasticities and skill technology. Productivity and motivation are uncorrelated. Low productivity, not low motivation, is the stronger predictor of academic struggles. School quality augments productivity and accelerates skill production. We find that dynamic skill complementarities arise mainly from children?s aging and from a feedback loop between investment activity and productivity rather than from carrying forward past skill stocks.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738479
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738479
Y2  - 2026/04/24
